### 1. One-Line Summary
- Nittaku G-1 is a grippy, medium-hard “spin-first” rubber with a higher ceiling and more stable power play, while Evolution FX-S is a softer, bouncier rubber that feels easier at low impact and favors quick topspin and comfort.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
- **Speed & Gears:**
    - **Low Impact:**
        - Evolution FX-S feels livelier and easier to produce pace with compact strokes; the softer sponge gives quick rebound and helps when you’re late.
        - Nittaku G-1 is more controlled and slightly quieter at low power; it rewards clean contact but won’t “give” as much free speed.
    - **Top End:**
        - Nittaku G-1 has the higher top gear when you drive through the sponge; it stays stable and heavy on full power loops/counters.
        - Evolution FX-S tops out earlier; you can still hit hard, but it compresses sooner and can feel less “solid” at max effort.
    - **Linearity:**
        - Nittaku G-1 is more linear/predictable as you add power—what you put in is what you get.
        - Evolution FX-S has a more springy, catapult-style response; great for easy depth, but can feel jumpier in touch/transition moments.

- **Spin Mechanics:**
    - **Opening Loop:**
        - Evolution FX-S is very friendly for opening: softer sponge grabs the ball easily and helps lift backspin with shorter motion.
        - Nittaku G-1 opens extremely well too, especially with good brushing; it prefers a slightly firmer, more “committed” contact for maximum bite.
    - **Max Spin:**
        - Nittaku G-1 generally produces heavier, more loaded spin at high swing speed; the harder feel supports strong acceleration and keeps the ball “weighted.”
        - Evolution FX-S gives high spin with less effort, but the absolute peak is typically lower than G-1 when both are struck at full speed.
    - **Topsheet Grip:**
        - Nittaku G-1’s topsheet is notably grippy and confidence-inspiring for brushing and spin variation.
        - Evolution FX-S is also grippy, but the softer overall feel makes it rely more on sponge engagement for “easy spin.”

- **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    - **Arc Height:**
        - Evolution FX-S tends to produce a naturally higher, safer arc on topspin—helpful for net clearance.
        - Nittaku G-1 is medium-high but more “driven” when you hit through; it can arc high on brush, then flatten nicely on power.
    - **Safety:**
        - Evolution FX-S offers strong over-the-net safety in topspin exchanges, especially on opening loops.
        - Nittaku G-1’s safety is excellent when your timing is solid; it is less “auto-arc” but more stable when the rally speeds up.

- **Feel & Feedback:**
    - **Sensation:**
        - Evolution FX-S feels softer, more cushioned, and more comfortable—good if you like a “ball-sinking” sensation.
        - Nittaku G-1 feels firmer and crisper with clearer feedback on contact quality.
    - **Dwell:**
        - Evolution FX-S has longer perceived dwell at low-to-mid impact because the sponge deforms easily.
        - Nittaku G-1’s dwell is more “topsheet-driven”: excellent on brush contact, then firmer once you engage the sponge.

- **Control & Short Game:**
    - **Sensitivity:**
        - Nittaku G-1 is grippy, so it reads incoming spin clearly; the firmer base helps keep it manageable if your technique is consistent.
        - Evolution FX-S can be slightly more sensitive in the short game due to catapult, especially if you relax the hand too much.
    - **Touch Play:**
        - Nittaku G-1 excels at short pushes, stops, and controlled flick setups because it doesn’t over-bounce easily.
        - Evolution FX-S makes short touch shots easy when you have soft hands, but depth control can require more attention because the sponge wants to spring.

- **Blocking & Countering:**
    - **Passive Block:**
        - Nittaku G-1 is steadier and less reactive; blocks land more predictably with a solid, “hold” feeling.
        - Evolution FX-S is comfortable but can rebound higher/longer if you don’t close the angle; softer sponge can get pressured by very heavy pace.
    - **Active Counter:**
        - Nittaku G-1 shines in punch blocks and counter topspin with forward intent—stable and heavy.
        - Evolution FX-S is quick and easy for compact counters; best when you prioritize timing and placement over brute force.

### 3. The Recommendation
- **Choose Nittaku G-1 if:**
    - You want a higher performance ceiling for power looping and counter-topspin.
    - You prefer a firmer, more direct feel with linear response and strong stability under pace.
    - Your game leans on heavy, loaded spin and controlled short-game depth.

- **Choose Evolution FX-S if:**
    - You want immediate ease: softer feel, faster low-impact rebound, and comfortable topspin.
    - You rely on quick openings, close-to-table topspin, and compact counters.
    - You value a higher natural arc and “forgiving” feel more than maximum top-end stability.